column295: I took many risks  resulting in a wide spectrum of possible results.
When the amount on hand is large  I tend to invest asset A less. When I have less money on hand  I tend to invest asset A more.

I had no pre-emptive strategy at all. I simply went off of patterns as the multipliers rose and fell. I did not understand any sort of strategy that could predict how to make the most money  and therefore my decisions were based solely on the fact that I had relatively nothing to lose if I was below $5.00  and therefore would invest more.

70%of the paths use aggresive tactics: 20% asset B  80% asset A. The rest of the time use a more conservative method: 60% asset B  40% asset A. And if my current amount is less than $5 I will simply throw all the money into asset A since earning little from asset B made little sense to me.

column289: NA - Clinical science graduate student; in undergrad psych and philosophy
column295: Know that each period was independent. I made investment decisions waiting for my amount to grow  then investing very little in asset A.
It's very random....but when I have a lot of money  I try to be conservative and hope to keep the money.

Very interesting. At first  I did not want to go for asset A  but over time I began to be more daring and invested in riskier ways. I did not quite understand the point of having the option to see the lowest  average  and highest but it was interesting to see the information.  |  | Around halfway  I began to go for around 90/10% for asset A/asset B for the first 3 periods and then about 65/35 after. When I lost a lot of money in the first 3 periods  I began to go for 100% asset A in order to get the chance to get my money back. As for the chance for asset C  I only paid $1 when I had at least $5 to spare.

I find it surprising that anyone chose a strategy other than 100% A every single time (the low-avg-high information during the last round made this clear). With A's 1.06 +- 55%  you had a roughly 80% chance of getting higher than investment B's 1.03 return  and at every single move 100% A gave a higher expected payoff. So  I predetermined that I would only go 100% A every single round. |  | I notice that I broke this pattern when the amount surpassed $200  as it did on two occasions. (I was crossing my fingers that one of these would be my payoff at the end!). These times I adjusted it so that I would have $200 guarenteed in B and the rest invested in A. I should not have done this as both times the returns only increased  but the idea of having a 1 in 15 shot of winning $200 was too much to pass up. |  | The buy a 4% chance of $20 was a horrible investment - it costs an expected $25 ($1*25 rounds) to win $20  and those are horrible odds. I clicked it once when I was at only ~$1 on the last round  but again this was a bad decision. |  | If I were to do this experiment again I would change nothing about my actions.

I decided to make risky decisions because they make the best payoffs. As a result  I got some extremely high numbers and some low numbers as well. It was difficult to construct a strategy to tackle this situation.
This is a great experience that is very similar to the investment in real world. The instructions are very clear and I understand them very well!
